# ✅ Next.js Error Boundary Examples

## ✅ Using **Next.js App Router** (recommended, Next.js 13+)

In the **App Router**, Next.js has **built‑in support** for Error Boundaries via `error.tsx`.

***

### 📁 Folder structure

```txt
app/
├── page.tsx
├── error.tsx        ← Error Boundary
├── loading.tsx
```

***

### `app/page.tsx`

```tsx
export default function Page() {
  // Client-side render error
  throw new Error("Client-side render error!");

  return <h1>Hello World</h1>;
}
```

***

### ✅ `app/error.tsx` (Error Boundary)

```tsx
'use client';

import { useEffect } from 'react';

export default function Error({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error;
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  useEffect(() => {
    console.error(error);
  }, [error]);

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Something went wrong!</h2>
      <p>{error.message}</p>

      <button onClick={() => reset()}>
        Try again
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

***

### ✅ What this catches

✅ Client‑side render errors  
✅ Hydration/runtime errors  
✅ Errors in child components

❌ SSR failures before HTML generation

***

## ✅ App Router with **Scoped Error Boundaries**

You can **limit the boundary to a route segment**:

```txt
app/
├── dashboard/
│   ├── page.tsx
│   ├── error.tsx   ← only for /dashboard
```

Only `/dashboard` is protected — the rest of the app is unaffected.

