## 1️⃣ Pages Router (`pages/`)

### 🔹 How error handling works

The Pages Router relies mostly on **React Error Boundaries** and **custom handling**.

#### ✅ Client‑side errors

Handled using **React Error Boundaries** — **after hydration only**.

```tsx
// components/ErrorBoundary.tsx
class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  state = { hasError: false };

  static getDerivedStateFromError() {
    return { hasError: true };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error, info) {
    console.error(error, info);
  }

  render() {
    return this.state.hasError
      ? <h1>Something went wrong</h1>
      : this.props.children;
  }
}
```

Wrapped in:

```tsx
// pages/_app.tsx
<ErrorBoundary>
  <Component {...pageProps} />
</ErrorBoundary>
```

✅ Catches **client‑side render/lifecycle errors**  
❌ Does **not** catch SSR crashes

***

### 🔹 SSR errors (Pages Router)

Handled manually using:

*   `getServerSideProps`
*   `getStaticProps`
*   `pages/_error.tsx`

```ts
export async function getServerSideProps() {
  try {
    // server logic
  } catch (err) {
    return { notFound: true };
  }
}
```

❗ **Key limitation**  
React Error Boundaries are **inactive during SSR**.

***

### 🔴 Pages Router limitations

*   ❌ No built‑in route‑level error isolation
*   ❌ No automatic retry/reset
*   ❌ Error boundaries don’t work on the server
*   ❌ Boilerplate-heavy

***

## 2️⃣ App Router (`app/`) ✅ **Modern & Recommended**

The App Router introduces **framework‑level error handling**, inspired by Remix.

***

### ✅ Built‑in Error Boundary: `error.tsx`

```txt
app/
├── dashboard/
│   ├── page.tsx
│   ├── error.tsx
```

```tsx
// app/dashboard/error.tsx
'use client';

export default function Error({ error, reset }) {
  return (
    <>
      <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
      <button onClick={() => reset()}>Retry</button>
    </>
  );
}
```

✅ Handles:

*   Client‑side render errors
*   Hydration/runtime errors
*   Errors in **Server Components**
*   Errors during data fetching

✅ Scoped **only** to `/dashboard`

